# n8n Integration (ops/raspberry-pi)

Instance: `https://n8n.bentenberge.com`. Operational context in `ops/raspberry-pi/context.md`.

## Two tools — use both

| Tool | Secrets? | Use for |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **n8n MCP** (`user-n8n-mcp`) | No | Workflow SDK: build, validate, update, execute; search nodes; assign credential IDs |
| **n8n REST API** | Yes (`N8N_API_KEY` in `ops/raspberry-pi/.env`) | Create token credentials; full JSON; executions |

Pattern: MCP builds workflow → API creates credentials from `.env` → MCP assigns credential IDs to nodes.

## Workflow build pipeline (MCP)

1. `get_sdk_reference` — read SDK patterns first
2. `search_nodes` / `get_suggested_nodes`
3. `get_node_types` — exact parameter names; never guess
4. `validate_workflow`
5. `create_workflow_from_code` or `update_workflow`

## Credentials

- **Token-based** (Telegram, OpenRouter): REST API `POST /api/v1/credentials`
- **OAuth** (Google Calendar): user must connect in n8n UI — not automatable

Existing creds: Nathan (`telegramApi`), OpenRouter Persoonlijk (`openRouterApi`), Google Calendar (OAuth, UI).

## Chat Hub vs Telegram

- `/home/chat?agentId=...` = n8n Personal Agent (browser only) — **not** callable from Telegram
- Telegram bots need **Telegram Trigger** + **AI Agent** workflow
- Chat Hub exposure: **Chat Trigger** with "Make Available in n8n Chat" + streaming AI Agent

## Secrets

- Local `.env` at `ops/raspberry-pi/.env` (gitignored) — see `.env.example`
- Never put real keys in committed docs or rules
